lines.text: Qanila Faheem
* Pakistan's longstanding 'Strategic depth' doctrine
has effectively transformed into a 'Strategic dilemma'
following Taliban's return to power. Critically analyse
the shift in the Taliban's posture from a 'Dependant
Proxy' to a Sovereign Nationalist' entity, and evaluate
the implications of the TTP-Taliban nexus for
Pakistan's internal security and regional standing
in the face of a rising Indian footprint in Kabul.
1) Introduction
2) Shift in Taliban's posture: From a 'Dependent
Proxy' to a 'Sovereign Nationalist' entity
2.1) Taliban's assertion of strategic autonomy
over dependence ended Pakistan's exclusive
influence
路 Taliban no longer acts as Islamabad's "subordinate"
L, rejecting demands to manage Pakistan's internal
security rejects strategic depth
路 Regime views past pakistani patronage as a 'colonial
hangover actively distances itself from 151 to build
domestic legitimacy as 'liberators'
路 Pursues an independent foreign policy, diversifying
partnerships with Iran, china, & notably India to
avoid over-reliance on Pakistan.
2.2) Talibans aspirations for an Islamic Emirate
